stylometry: @risk works by running the same simulation with multiple input variables. When you run a simulation with 5 inputs it looks at each of those inputs with 1000 iterations. The data is analized by imputing the different inputs in to the same model and then telling you the mean of those iterations, it also tells you the standard deviation, so you can sellect the best input. This show you the risk associated with each input, a high mean with a low standard deviation is an option that has a high profit with a minimal risk associated with it.
